&gt; _&quot;... I want it to be more specific and make them choose either a Y or a N and any other value will tell them that they need to answer with a Y or a N.&quot;_

Use a _[Boolean](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/20/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/Boolean.html)_ value to determine whether the loop should be exited or not.  
And, set it&#39;s value from within the loop.

Use the _Boolean_ object, also, as opposed to a _boolean_ primitive.  
This way, you can use a _null_ value for invalid entries.

```java
public static void main(String[] args) {
    Boolean exit = null;
    do {
        System.out.print(&quot;Do you want to play again ([Y] / n)?&quot;);
        userInput = inputScanner.nextLine();
        System.out.println(userInput);
        if (userInput.equalsIgnoreCase(&quot;y&quot;) || userInput.equalsIgnoreCase(&quot;yes&quot;)) {
            exit = false;
        } else if (userInput.equalsIgnoreCase(&quot;n&quot;) || userInput.equalsIgnoreCase(&quot;no&quot;)) {
            exit = true;
        } else {
            exit = null;
            System.out.println(&quot;Invalid entry, try again.&quot;);
        }
    } while (exit == null || !exit);
    //     System.out.println(&quot;Thanks for playing!&quot;);
}
```

Here is an example input and output.

```none
Do you want to play again ([Y] / n)?abc
abc
Invalid entry, try again.
Do you want to play again ([Y] / n)?y
y
Do you want to play again ([Y] / n)?n
n
```

I put the code in a method, you can use this code in the main method -&gt;
```
import java.util.Scanner;

public class Play {  
	static Scanner inputScanner = new Scanner(System.in);
	static String userInput = &quot;&quot;;
	
