A quick summary of what this code does :-

 1. converts `userInput` into smaller case for flexibility which allows input like &quot;yEs&quot;. You could use `userInput.equalsIgnoreCase()` too.
 2. checks whether userInput is equal to &quot;yes&quot; or &quot;no&quot; / &quot;y&quot; or &quot;n&quot;
 3. if `userInput` is not &quot;yes&quot;..., sends an error message requesting the user to use &quot;yes&quot;...
 4. if `userInput` is &quot;yes&quot;..., checks if it is &quot;yes&quot; or &quot;no&quot;
 5. if it is yes it continues the game, else it says &quot;Thank you for playing&quot; and exits the game

if done correctly you can end up with your output looking like this -&gt;
```
Do you want to play again ([Y] / [N])?a
Incorrect reply &#39;a&#39;, use [Y] / [N] or [Yes] / [No]
Do you want to play again ([Y] / [N])?b
Incorrect reply &#39;b&#39;, use [Y] / [N] or [Yes] / [No]
Do you want to play again ([Y] / [N])?n
Thank you for playing!
```
