I have come across this situation at work. Below is what I&#39;ve come up with. The idea is to override Lombok&#39;s `protected User(User.UserBuilder b)` method

```java
@Data
@Builder
public class User {
    private static final PasswordEncoder ENCODER = new BCryptPasswordEncoder();

    private String password;
    private Integer otherField;

    protected User(final User.UserBuilder&lt;?, ?&gt; b) {
        setPassword(b.password);
        otherField = b.otherField;
    }

    public void setPassword(String password) {
        Assert.notNull(password);
        this.password = ENCODER.encode(password);
    }
}
```

Just want to mention the alternative to **define the Builder on a custom constructor** instead of defining it on the class level. 

    @Data
    public class User {
        private static final PasswordEncoder ENCODER = new BCryptPasswordEncoder();

        private String password = null;
        private Instant timestamp = Instant.now();

        // The builder now calls this constructor when build() is called
        @Builder
        public User(String password) {
            setPassword(password);
        }

        public void setPassword(String password) {
            Assert.notNull(password);
            this.password = ENCODER.encode(password);
        }
    }

It is quite similar to &quot;Custom setter and constructor&quot; of Jan Nielsen, but offers a bit more control. 

 - Constructor and Builder are &quot;in sync&quot;, the Builder uses the same path to construct objects
 - You don&#39;t necessarily need to add all fields to the constructor
 - Omitted fields are not accessible in the Builder (field `timestamp` in the example)

